            <fr:title text="Boolean valuations: disjunction">Boolean valuations: disjunction</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>         For disjunction, Boolean valuations work the following way: they make a disjunction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex> true exactly when they make <html:em>at least one</html:em> of the components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> true.
        To see why, think about "the moon is made of green cheese or Carl is a good dog".
        Is this true or false?
        This seems to be true: the truth of the second part is enough for the whole thing to be true.
        So for disjunction, we want to be sure to pick a table that respects this.
        The only way for a disjunction to be false, on this way of proceeding, is for both of its components to be false; any other combination makes the disjunction true.</html:p>
            <html:p>Note in particular the connection between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \lor  \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:link href="/lectures/000E/" title="Logicians' Weird Habit 1" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/000E/" display-uri="000E" type="local">logicians' weird habit 1</fr:link>.
        Whenever I say "or" in these notes, I mean to include the possibility of both sides of the "or" being true.
        And that's just what <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex> does as well, on this scheme.
        This is a case of life imitating art; what's happening here is that uses of the English word "or" among communities of logicians are strongly influenced by experiences with the connective <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>         Just as with conjunction, we can record this policy in a table:
</html:p>
